Exhibit 1 - FORM OF GAS TRANSPORTATION SERVICE REQUEST
1. PRELIMINARY STATEMENT
1.1 Public Service Company of Colorado ("Transporter") owns and operates a certain natural gas pipeline system (the "Pipeline System") located wholly within the State of Colorado, by and through which Transporter purchases, sells and distributes natural gas for retail to residential and commercial customers and transports natural gas to industrial, commercial and residential customers, all of which is subject to the jurisdiction of the Colorado Public Utilities Commission under the Colorado Public Utilities Law, C.R.S. ?? 40-1-101, et seq. Such natural gas sales and transportation services are exempt from the jurisdiction of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission ("FERC") under the Natural Gas Act, 15 U.S.C. ?? 717, et seq., pursuant to the local distribution exemption under Section 1(b) of the Natural Gas Act, 15 U.S.C. ? 717(b), and the "Hinshaw" exemption under Section 1(c) of the Natural Gas Act, 15 U.S.C. ? 717(c). Transporter also uses the Pipeline System to provide certain gas transportation in interstate commerce pursuant to a limited-jurisdiction, blanket certificate of public convenience and necessity issued by the FERC pursuant to Section 284.224 of the FERC's regulations (18 C.F.R. ? 284.224) on October 8, 1992, in Docket No. CP92-633-000. 61 FERC ? 62,012 (1992). This FERC certificate authorizes Public Service to engage in the transportation of natural gas in interstate commerce to the same extent and in the same manner that intrastate pipelines are authorized to engage in such transportation under Section 311(a)(2) of the Natural Gas Policy Act. 15 U.S.C. ? 3371(a)(2).
1.2 This Statement of Operating Conditions ("Operating Statement") describes the administrative and operational policies and procedures of Transporter regarding Firm and Interruptible gas transportation services provided by Transporter in interstate commerce pursuant to its aforementioned limited-jurisdiction, blanket certificate issued by the FERC under 18 C.F.R. ? 284.224. All Gas Transportation Service Agreements are hereby expressly made subject to this Operating Statement, as it may be amended from time to time.
1.3 It is the policy of Transporter to consider all service requests in light of its existing commitments, pipeline design capacity, available pipeline capacity, available Receipt Point(s) and Delivery Point(s), and other factors deemed material by Transporter. Transporter reserves the right, pursuant to arms-length negotiations with any requesting Shipper, to vary from these general terms and conditions when commercial or operational conditions dictate, provided that such variations are not materially detrimental and/or unduly discriminatory to any other Shipper similarly situated.
1.4 If any conflict arises between the provisions of this Operating Statement and a Gas Transportation Service Agreement, the provisions of this Operating Statement will control with regard to such conflict. Notwithstanding any other provision that may be construed to the contrary, Transporter reserves the right to revise this Operating Statement to adopt any or all standards heretofore or hereafter adopted by the North American Energy Standards Board or to make any other revisions Transporter deems appropriate. Upon revision to this Operating Statement, Transporter will make notice thereof available to each Shipper via its "NOTICES" E-mail address as provided for in Section 18 (Notices) set forth in such Shipper's Gas Transportation Service Agreement below.
2. DEFINITIONS
Except as otherwise specified, the following terms as used herein and in the Gas Transportation Service Agreement will be construed to have the following scope and meaning:
2.1 "Agent" means a third party who has the authority to exercise certain or all rights and/or perform certain or all obligations set forth in the Gas Transportation Service Agreement for the benefit of the Shipper(s). The Agent and the Shipper may be one and the same.
2.2 "Authorized Overrun" means the quantity of gas authorized by Transporter in excess of the MDQ, as specified in the applicable transportation service agreement.
2.3 "Btu" means one (1) International Table Btu, or BtuIT, which is a unit of energy defined in the International Steam Table, where 1 BtuIT = 1055.056 joules.
2.4 "BTU Adjusted Area" means the portion of Transporter's Pipeline System where gas is blended with air or inert gas in order to meet Wobbe delivery specifications.
2.5 "BTU Non-Adjusted Area" means the portion of Transporter's Pipeline System where there is no additional requirement for gas to be blended with air or inert gas in order to meet the Wobbe delivery specifications.
2.6 "Business Day" means all non-Holiday weekdays.
2.7 "Central Clock Time" or "CCT" means Central Standard Time, except for that period when daylight savings time is in effect. During this daylight savings time period, CCT shall mean Central Daylight Time.
2.8 "CIG TI Transportation Rate" means the maximum transportation commodity rate (per Dth), including applicable charges for fuel, lost and unaccounted-for gas, and all other applicable surcharges and fees in effect from time to time for interruptible transportation service under Rate Schedule TI-1, or successor rate schedule, of Colorado Interstate Gas Company's (CIG) Federal Energy Regulatory Commission gas tariff.
2.9 "Colorado PUC" shall mean the Colorado Public Utilities Commission or any state commission, agency or other Colorado governmental body or bodies succeeding to, lawfully exercising or superseding any powers which are exercisable by the Colorado Public Utilities Commission.
2.10 "Credit Rating" means, with respect to an entity on any date of determination, the rating then assigned to such entity's unsecured and senior unsubordinated long-term debt obligations (not supported by third-party credit enhancement) by Standards and Poor's ("S&P") or Moody's.
2.11 "Credit Support Provider" means an entity providing a Guarantee, whose lowest Credit Rating is at least BBB- by S&P or Baa3 by Moody's.
2.12 "Cubic foot of gas" means the volume of water-free gas which would occupy a space of one (1) cubic foot at a temperature of 60 degrees Fahrenheit and at a pressure of 14.73 pounds per square inch absolute.
2.13 "Dekatherm" or "Dth" means one (1) Dth is the energy equivalent to 10 therms, or 1,000,000 Btu (1 MMBtu). One (1) therm is the energy equivalent to 100,000 Btu.
2.14 "Delivery Point(s)" means the point of interconnection between the Pipeline System and the facilities of the Interconnecting Party(s) where Transporter delivers gas for the account of Shipper after transportation on the Pipeline System, as specified on an Exhibit to the Gas Transportation Service Agreement.
2.15 "Electronic Bulletin Board" or "EBB" means the World Wide Web Site established and maintained by Transporter for the purpose of identifying the day-to-day procedures, communications protocols, business practices, Nominations and Imbalance management for transportation service on Transporter's system. If there are inconsistencies between the web site and this Operating Statement, the Operating Statement shall control.
2.16 "Equivalent Quantity" means the sum of the quantities of gas, measured in dekatherms, received by Transporter for the account of Shipper at the Receipt Point(s) during any given period-of-time, after any applicable reduction for Fuel Reimbursement. The quantities of gas, measured in dekatherms, delivered at the Delivery Point(s) after transportation shall be equal to the quantities of gas received at the Receipt Point(s) for transportation, after reduction for Fuel Reimbursement.
2.17 "FERC" shall mean the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission or any federal commission, agency or other governmental body or bodies succeeding to, lawfully exercising or superseding any powers which are exercisable by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission.
2.18 "Firm" means transportation service that has the highest priority of transportation service offered by Transporter under this Operating Statement.
2.19 "Force Majeure" shall include without limitation by this recital, acts of God including fires, explosions, earthquakes, or volcanic eruptions, storms, floods, extreme cold, freezing, washouts; necessity for compliance with any court order, law, regulation or ordinance promulgated by any governmental authority having jurisdiction, either federal, state or local, civil or military; acts of a public enemy; wars; civil disturbances; strikes, lockouts or other industrial disturbances; shutdowns for purposes of necessary repairs, relocations, or construction of facilities, breakage or accident to machinery or lines of pipe; necessity for testing (as required by governmental authority or as deemed necessary for safe operation by the testing party); inability of either Party to obtain necessary compliance with any obligation or condition of this Operating Statement, materials supplies, permits, or labor to perform or; inability to obtain rights-of-way; and any other causes, whether of the kind herein recited or not, which are not reasonably in the control of the Party claiming suspension.
2.20 "Fuel Reimbursement" or "Fuel Reimbursement Percentage" means the quantity of gas that Shipper shall be responsible for providing Transporter at the Receipt Point(s) to compensate Transporter for Shipper's allocable share of the gas used by Transporter for fuel , and for gas lost and unaccounted for in the Pipeline System, stated in terms of a percentage of the physical quantities received into the Pipeline System. The Maximum Fuel Reimbursement Percentage, as reflected from time-to-time in the Statement of Rates, shall be computed and adjusted annually for each calendar year as set forth in Section 11. The Fuel Reimbursement Percentage applicable to each Shipper shall be as reflected in the Shipper's Gas Transportation Service Agreement and may be discounted to reflect the relative use of the Pipeline System necessary for Transporter to perform the transportation under Shipper's Gas Transportation Service Agreement.
2.21 "Gas" or "Natural Gas" means any mixture of hydrocarbons consisting essentially of methane. These terms need not be capitalized to have this meaning.
2.22 "Gas Day" means a period of twenty-four (24) consecutive-hours beginning and ending at 9:00 a.m. CCT. The reference date for any Gas Day shall be the date at the beginning of such 24-hour period.
2.23 "Gas Transportation Service Agreement" means the agreement entered into between Transporter and Shipper providing for the transportation by Transporter of Shipper's Gas from the Receipt Point(s) through the Pipeline System to the Delivery Point(s) pursuant to this Operating Statement.
2.24 "Gross heating value" means the heat energy generated by complete stoichiometric combustion in air of one (1) cubic foot of dry gas at standard conditions (14.73 psia, 60?F), where the products of combustion are returned to 60? Fahrenheit and water produced by combustion is condensed to the liquid state.
2.25. "Guarantee" means a guarantee of the obligations of Shipper which is provided by Shipper's Credit Support Provider in favor of Transporter, with such form of guarantee being acceptable to Transporter.
2.26. "Holiday" means New Year's Day, Martin Luther King, Jr. Day, Presidents' Day, Memorial Day, Independence Day, Labor Day, Frances Xavier Cabrini Day, Veterans Day, Thanksgiving Day, and Christmas Day.
2.27 "Imbalance" means the difference between the quantity of Shipper's Gas received by Transporter at the Receipt Point(s), less Fuel Reimbursement, and the quantity of gas delivered at the Delivery Point(s) for Shipper's account.
2.28 "Imbalance Resolution Gas" means the quantity of gas necessary to correct any cumulative Imbalance for Shipper's account.
2.29 "Index Price One" means the gas commodity market index price equal to the highest reported "Weekly Weighted Average Price" for CIG Rocky Mountains, as published by Platt's Gas Daily on the first Business Day of each week of a four-week period, where the first applicable "Weekly Weighted Average Price" for each such four-week period includes the fourth calendar day of the Month. Should Platt's Gas Daily become unavailable, Transporter shall determine the highest weekly average index price based on information posted in a similar publication.
2.30 "Index Price Two" means the gas commodity market index price equal to the lowest reported "Weekly Weighted Average Price" for CIG Rocky Mountains, as published by Platt's Gas Daily on the first Business Day of each week of a four-week period, where the first applicable "Weekly Weighted Average Price" for each such four-week period includes the fourth calendar day of the Month. Should Platt's Gas Daily become unavailable, Transporter shall determine the lowest weekly average index price based on information posted in a similar publication.
2.31 "Interconnecting Party" means the operator of the facilities immediately upstream of the Receipt Point(s) or the operator of the facilities immediately downstream of the Delivery Point(s).
2.32 "Interstate Pipeline" shall have the same meaning as provided in Section 2(16) of the Natural Gas Policy Act of 1978, as amended, ("NGPA") and Part 284 of the regulations of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission.
2.33 "Interruptible" means transportation service provided for under this Operating Statement which is of lesser priority and quality as compared that of Firm transportation service provided under this Operating Statement.
2.34 "Interruption" means reducing, suspending or discontinuing either the receipt or delivery of gas.
2.35 "Master Point List" means a listing of all currently available Receipt Point(s) as provided on Transporter's EBB.
2.36 "Maximum Daily Quantity" or "MDQ") means the maximum daily quantity of gas expressed in Dekatherms. Transporter is obligated to transport for Shipper as set forth on an Exhibit to the Firm Gas Transportation Service Agreement. Transporter may agree from time to time to transport on an interruptible basis for Shipper, as set forth on an Exhibit to the Interruptible Gas Transportation Service Agreement. This term is used interchangeably with Maximum Daily Contract Quantity, or MDCQ, as well as Maximum Daily Transportation Quantity, or MDTQ.
2.37 "Mcf" means 1,000 cubic feet of gas.
2.38 "MMBtu" means one (1) million (1,000,000) Btu.
2.39 "Month" means the period beginning at 9:00 a.m. Central Clock Time on the first day of a calendar month and ending at 8:59 a.m. Central Clock time on the same day of the following calendar month.
2.40 "NAESB Standards" or "NAESB WGQ Standards" means the business practices and electronic communication practices, protocols and processes promulgated by the North American Energy Standards Board (also known as the Wholesale Gas Quadrant or the Gas Industry Standards Board).
2.41 "Nomination" means the physical Quantity of gas that a Shipper requests to transport on the Transporter's Pipeline System for a specific Gas Day. Nominations are to be adjusted to include Fuel Reimbursement and shall be made on a Dekatherm basis.
2.42 "OFO Tolerance Level" means the quantity or percentage of the total transportation quantity specified in an Operational Flow Order that can be under- or over-delivered to an Operational Area by a Shipper during the period of an Operational Flow Order without incurring additional charges.
2.43 "On Peak Demand Quantity" means the maximum daily firm capacity that a Shipper with an Interruptible Gas Transportation Service Agreement may purchase from Transporter, with the applicable maximum quantity set forth in Shipper's Service Agreement or amendments thereto.
2.44 "Operational Area" means the regional areas of Transporter's System consisting of pipeline facilities that receive and deliver Gas that is regularly commingled and interchanged with other gas supplies received and delivered in that Operational Area. Operational Areas are posted on Transporter's EBB. Receiving Parties under a Service Agreement shall be grouped under a specific Operational Area based on their location. The location of Delivery Points shall determine the Operational Area under which the Service Agreement shall be grouped.
2.45 "Operational Flow Order" or "OFO" means an order issued by Transporter as allowed by this tariff to alleviate conditions that threaten or could threaten the safe operation or integrity of Transporter's System or to maintain operations required to provide efficient and reliable firm gas service, which is issued for all or a specific portion of a Gas Day(s) and covering either a designated Operational Area, or a designated Shipper or group of Shippers within an Operational Area that Transporter reasonably believes are causing the condition necessitating the OFO.
2.46 "Party" means either Transporter or Shipper, as the case may be, and "Parties" shall mean both Transporter and Shipper, except where the reference is to the Interconnecting Party or Interconnecting Parties.
2.47 "Pipeline System" means the pipelines, compressor stations, regulator stations, meters, gas processing facilities and other related facilities owned by Transporter and utilized in providing transportation service.
2.48 "Primary Receipt Point(s)" means Receipt Point(s) specified in the Service Agreement or amendments thereto as Primary Receipt Point(s) where Receiving Party is entitled to Firm Gas Transportation Service on Transporter's System.
2.49 "Psia" means pressure in pounds per square inch absolute.
2.50 "Receipt Point(s)" means the interconnect wherein Transporter receives gas tendered by or for the account of Shipper for transportation on Transporter's Pipeline System. Receipt Point(s) are specified in the Service Agreement or amendments thereto and/or in the Master Point List on Transporter's EBB.
2.51 "Request for Gas Transportation Service" means a written request for transportation service submitted by any prospective Shipper as provided in this Operating Statement.
2.52 "Secondary Delivery Point(s)" means Authorized Delivery Point(s) that is not considered as a Primary Delivery Point(s).
2.53 "Secondary Receipt Point(s)" means Authorized Receipt Point(s) that are not on the Master Point List as Primary Receipt Point(s).
2.54 "Shipper" means the party that holds lawful right and title to the gas that is being transported, and any Party who (a) is receiving service in accordance with this Operating Statement, (b) has executed a Gas Transportation Service Agreement, or (c) has completed a request for service under Section 5 of this Operating Statement.
2.55 "Shipper's Gas" means gas for which title is held by the Shipper under a Service Agreement.
2.56 "Transporter" means Public Service Company of Colorado, a corporation under the laws of the state of Colorado, also sometimes referred to as the Company.
2.57 "Unauthorized Overrun Penalty" means an amount charged (i) to a Shipper in the event a Shipper's deliveries exceed an Operational Flow Order Tolerance Level; (ii) to a Shipper receiving Firm Transportation Service or the On Peak Demand Quantity Option under Interruptible Transportation Service that fails to comply with an order by Transporter directing the Shipper to a Primary Receipt Point and such Shipper continues to use Secondary Receipt Point(s); or (iii) to an Interruptible Transportation Shipper transporting Gas above its On Peak Demand Quantity in the event of an Interruption. Transporter will provide Shipper notice of the applicable Unauthorized Overrun Penalty.
2.58 "Year" means a period of three hundred sixty-five (365) consecutive days or three hundred sixty-six (366) consecutive days if such period includes February 29, beginning January 1, unless otherwise specified.
3. SERVICES, RATE ELECTION AND CHARGES
3.1 Service Availability. Gas transportation service on the Pipeline System, i.e., either Firm transportation service or Interruptible transportation service, is available on behalf of any person (Shipper) for the transportation of gas, ultimately destined for delivery into any Interstate Pipeline, from any Receipt Point(s) to any Delivery Point(s) on the Pipeline System in accordance with 18 C.F.R. Part 284. Transporter shall provide service on a first-come, first served basis, provided:
(a) Shipper has complied with all service request requirements set forth in Section 5 and Section 19 of this Operating Statement;
(b) Transporter has the capability to provide such service consistent with its other obligations under this Operating Statement;
(c) For Firm transportation service, the Pipeline System has sufficient capacity to provide such Firm transportation service during the time period requested; and
(d) Shipper and Transporter have executed a Gas Transportation Service Agreement in a form substantially the same as set forth in this Operating Statement. Nothing in this Operating Statement shall be deemed to obligate Transporter to render any service for any Shipper until a Gas Transportation Service Agreement has been entered into and duly executed by both Parties. Additionally, Transporter shall not be required to provide any service if: (i) Shipper fails to remit payment; (ii) Shipper fails to provide Transporter sufficient quantities of Shipper's Gas to meet the daily load requirements under the Service Agreement; (iii) Transporter determines, based on its credit analysis, that the requesting party does not satisfy Transporter's credit requirements; (iv) the service requested would require the construction, modification, expansion or acquisition of any facility; (v) Shipper fails to modify nominations as directed by Transporter to reduce an imbalance; (vi) Shipper fails to comply with order to a Primary Receipt Point; or; or (vii) the service requested would not comply with the Operating Statement then in effect or the applicable Gas Transportation Service Agreement.
3.2 Rate Election. Transporter has elected pursuant to 18 C.F.R. ? 284.123(b)(1)(ii) to use for transportation service provided under this Operating Statement the rates established under its transportation rate schedules in effect from time to time for intrastate service contained in its state gas tariff on file with the Colorado PUC which Transporter has determined covers comparable service. Specifically, the rates and charges for Firm Transportation Service under this Operating Statement shall be equal to the applicable rates for service provided by Transporter under its TFL Rate Schedule as part of its Colorado PUC gas tariff and the rates and charges for Interruptible Transportation Service under this Operating Statement shall be equal to the applicable rates for service provided by Transporter under its TI Rate Schedule as part of its Colorado PUC gas tariff, including any effective General Rate Schedule Adjustment ("GRSA") or Pipeline System Integrity Adjustment ("PSIA") applicable to such rate schedules, but excluding any other rate adjustments, rate riders or other similar charges applicable to transportation service subject to Transporter's Colorado PUC gas tariff. Notwithstanding this provision, Transporter and Shipper may mutually agree upon a discounted rate that varies from the maximum rate established. Transporter may from time to time file with the Colorado PUC to change the applicable rates for transportation service under its TFL and TI rate schedules and, upon the effective of date of such change, may file a revised Statement of Rates reflecting such changed rates applicable to service under this Operating Statement. Transporter shall be entitled to implement such changed rates for service rendered to Shipper under this Operating Statement on their effective dates, unless otherwise provided in Shipper's Gas Transportation Service Agreement. Nothing in this section limits Shipper's rights to contest such changes, nor limits the rights of Shipper and Transporter to provide for lawful changes in rates through the terms of the Gas Transportation Service Agreement.
3.3 Services.
(a) Firm Transportation Service. Subject to this Operating Statement and the applicable Gas Transportation Service Agreement, Shipper shall cause to be delivered, and Transporter shall receive from Shipper, daily quantities of gas (including applicable Fuel Reimbursement) at the Receipt Point(s), and Transporter shall transport and deliver, and Shipper shall cause to be received, an Equivalent Quantity of gas up to Shipper's MDQ at the Delivery Point(s), such receipts and deliveries to be as nominated by Shipper and confirmed and scheduled by Transporter pursuant to Section 6 below. Firm transportation service shall not be subject to curtailment or Interruption except as provided for in this Operating Statement.
(1) All charges for Firm gas transportation service shall be as set forth in the currently effective Statement of Rates, as adjusted from time to time. The charges shall include the following:
(A) Firm Reservation Capacity Charge: A Monthly reservation charge equal to the product of the applicable Firm Reservation Capacity Charge rate (stated on a per Month basis) multiplied by the MDQ, as specified in the Gas Transportation Service Agreement. The Firm Reservation Capacity Charge shall be as set forth in the Gas Transportation Service Agreement and shall be no more than the maximum nor less than the minimum rate specified in the Statement of Rates. Shipper shall be obligated to pay the Firm Reservation Capacity Charge beginning with the effective date set forth in the Gas Transportation Service Agreement. If the effective date of any Firm Gas Transportation Service Agreement occurs on any day other than the first day of a month, or the termination of any Firm Gas Transportation Service Agreement occurs on any day other than the last day of a month, then the MDQ used in the calculation of the Firm Reservation Capacity Charge for such partial month shall be based on the ratio of the number of days that the Firm Gas Transportation Service Agreement was in effect to the total number of days in such Month.
(B) Commodity Charge: A Monthly charge equal to the product of the applicable Commodity Charge rate multiplied by each Dekatherm of gas that Transporter delivers for Shipper's account during each such Month. The Commodity Charge shall be as set forth in the Firm Gas Transportation Service Agreement or any amendment and shall be no more than the maximum nor less than the minimum rate specified in the Statement of Rates.
(C) Authorized Overrun Charge: A Monthly charge equal to the product of the applicable Authorized Overrun Charge rate multiplied by each Dekatherm for which Shipper receives authorization to overrun its MDQ during such Month.
(D) Fuel Reimbursement: The amount of gas for Fuel Reimbursement determined in accordance with Section 11 below.
(2) The availability of Firm transportation service will be limited by Transporter's determination as to whether it has sufficient available capacity to perform the service requested by Shipper.
(b) Interruptible Transportation Service. Subject to this Operating Statement and the applicable Gas Transportation Service Agreement, Shipper shall cause to be delivered, and Transporter shall receive from Shipper on an interruptible basis, daily quantities of gas (including applicable Fuel Reimbursement) at the Receipt Point(s), and Transporter shall transport and deliver on an interruptible basis, and Shipper shall cause to be received, an Equivalent Quantity of gas up to Shipper's MDQ at the Delivery Point(s), such receipts and deliveries to be as nominated by Shipper and confirmed and scheduled by Transporter pursuant to Section 6 below. Interruptible transportation service shall be subject to curtailment and/or Interruption as provided in Section 9 of this Operating Statement.
Shippers desiring interruptible Transportation Service are required to submit to Transporter a request for transportation service for each Delivery Point which contains the MDQ for which Shipper desires Transporter to provide interruptible capacity from its system, as well as, if applicable and approved by the Transporter, the On Peak Demand Quantity for which Shipper desires Transporter to provide firm capacity from its system. Additional terms of Interruptible Transportation Service shall be as set forth in the applicable Service Agreement, including the Transporter's Gas Tariff, Rules and Regulations Applicable to all Natural Gas Services and the Gas Transportation Terms and Conditions.
Interruptible Transportation Service is subject to availability of System capacity in Transporter's System. Should Transporter determine that adequate System capacity is unavailable, then Shipper is subject to immediate Interruption of Transportation Service. The terms of Interruptible Transportation Service provided to a Shipper, as well as any On Peak Demand Quantity provided to Shipper, shall be as set forth in the Shipper's Interruptible Gas Transportation Service Agreement or amendments thereto and Transporter's Gas tariff.
(1) All charges for Interruptible gas transportation service shall be as set forth in the currently effective Statement of Rates, as adjusted from time to time. The charges shall include the following:
(A) Commodity Charge: A Monthly charge equal to the product of the applicable Commodity Charge rate multiplied by each Dekatherm of gas that Transporter delivers for Shipper's account during each such Month. The Commodity Charge shall be as set forth in the Interruptible Gas Transportation Service Agreement or any amendment and shall be no more than the maximum nor less than the minimum rate specified in the Statement of Rates.
(B) Unauthorized Overrun Penalty: The Unauthorized Overrun Penalty shall apply as set forth in Section 2.57 This Unauthorized Overrun Penalty shall be in addition to all other applicable charges.
(C) Fuel Reimbursement: The amount of gas for Fuel Reimbursement determined in accordance with Section 11 below.
(2) Transporter reserves the right to not offer, not commence, or discontinue any Interruptible service if any impairment of Firm service could result.
(D) On Peak Demand Quantity Option: Under the On Peak Demand Quantity Option, Shipper may purchase from Transporter maximum daily firm capacity, referred to as On Peak Demand Quantity, subject to approval by Transporter. Such On Peak Demand Quantity will be set forth in Shipper's Service Agreement or amendments thereto. Additional terms applicable to On Peak Demand Quantity are set forth in the Transporter's Transportation Terms and Conditions.
Commitments for an On Peak Demand Quantity shall be at the option of Transporter, dependent upon the sufficiency of pipeline and System capacity with respect to the requirements of Transporter's other firm gas sales Customers and firm Shippers. Such quantities shall be requested and approved in accordance with the Initiating and Amending Gas Transportation Service section of these Gas Transportation Terms and Conditions.
The maximum daily On Peak Demand Quantity to be supplied for any Delivery Point shall be as specified in the Service Agreement or amendments thereto. Upon approval of the On Peak Demand Quantity, Shipper may nominate firm capacity up to the On Peak Demand Quantity specified in Shipper's Service Agreement or amendments thereto. Such Nominations shall be made in accordance with Transporter's Nomination procedures. Transporter may accept or reject Nominations in excess of the On Peak Demand Quantity at its discretion. Accepted Nominations in excess of the On Peak Demand Quantity shall be made available on an interruptible basis.
3.4 Fuel Reimbursement. Fuel Reimbursement shall be paid in kind at Shipper's Receipt Point(s) for Firm and Interruptible transportation service, and Overrun service, as applicable, all as set forth in the Gas Transportation Service Agreement.
4. OPERATING PROVISIONS
4.1 To protect the integrity of its Pipeline System or to meet its Firm obligations to other Shippers, Transporter shall have the right to require Shipper to balance its receipts and deliveries at any time, without liability to Transporter.
4.2 Shipper shall cause gas to be delivered to Transporter by the Interconnecting Party(s) at a constant rate throughout the Gas Day equal to an hourly flow rate of 1/24th of daily Nomination. If gas is delivered to Transporter by the Interconnecting Party(s) at an inconsistent rate and Transporter's operations are negatively affected, Transporter shall have authority to restrict Shipper's quantities or adjust Shipper's Nomination to an amount equal to the delivered rate by the Interconnecting Party(s).
4.3 Shipper is responsible for obtaining Shipper's Gas, nominating receipts and deliveries, managing Imbalances and payment of all costs of such gas, and for the transportation of such gas to Transporter's Receipt Point(s) from the Interconnecting Party(s). Shipper shall deliver or cause to be delivered to Transporter at the Receipt Point(s) any gas which Shipper desires to have transported, plus applicable Fuel Reimbursement. Shipper shall also receive or cause to be received gas delivered by Transporter at the Delivery Point(s).
4.4 If Shipper has multiple Gas Transportation Service Agreements with Transporter, Shipper shall not be permitted to combine services available under such Gas Transportation Service Agreements. Specifically, gas shall be received under a particular Gas Transportation Service Agreement and shall be delivered under that same Gas Transportation Service Agreement.
4.5 Transporter may take such action as reasonably necessary to prevent damage to or material deterioration of its Pipeline System and to maintain the operational integrity of the Pipeline System.
5. REQUEST FOR GAS TRANSPORTATION SERVICE
5.1 A Gas Transportation Service Agreement is required for all services hereunder. Any potential Shipper wishing to obtain services from Transporter shall submit in writing to Transporter a request for a Gas Transportation Service Agreement. The potential Shipper shall provide information requested by Transporter if necessary to adequately examine such potential Shipper's request. A standard request form is provided for this purpose as part this Operating Statement. If Transporter and the potential Shipper mutually agree to the rate(s) that the potential Shipper will pay for transportation service, then Transporter shall, subject to the execution of a Gas Transportation Service Agreement, endeavor to provide service within the time specified in the written request. The potential Shipper's request of a Gas Transportation Service Agreement shall be considered complete only if the information specified in Section 5.2 is provided in writing via U.S. first-class certified mail return receipt requested, overnight courier, E-mail, or hand delivery by an independent third party to the address listed below.
Requests should be sent to: Public Service Company of Colorado Natural Gas Services 1800 Larimer St., Suite 500 Denver, CO 80202
5.2 Each request for service shall include the following information:
(a) Potential Shipper's name, address, representative, telephone number, and e-mail address, if available.
(b) Type of service requested: Firm transportation, Interruptible transportation.
(c) Receipt Point(s) and Delivery Point(s) for all services, including the MDQ applicable to each point.
(d) MDQ, as applicable, for the requested Gas Transportation Service Agreement.
(e) Term of Gas Transportation Service Agreement, including the date service is requested to commence and the date service is requested to terminate.
(f) 24-hour contact information for Shipper and Point Operator(s) at Shipper's requested Receipt Point(s) and Delivery Point(s).
(g) All credit information required by Transporter.
(h) Other requested provisions, such as quality specifications for gas delivered upstream of a processing facility.
5.3 Service requests by potential Shippers for Firm transportation shall be processed on a first-come, first-served basis. That is, capacity for Firm service shall be allocated to the first Shipper with a valid request that contains the acceptable items listed under Section 5.2, subject, however, at all times to Transporter's satisfactory credit appraisal.

Upon its approval of such request, Transporter shall submit an amendment to Shipper and Shipper will execute an amendment to effectuate the change. Any Shipper who wishes to amend the Delivery Point(s) identified in its Gas Transportation Service Agreement shall submit a request to Transporter. 8. PRIORITY OF SERVICE
8.1 From time to time, Transporter may determine that it does not have sufficient capacity to accommodate all Nominations for service through a Receipt Point, Delivery Point, or segment of its Pipeline System ("Constrained Point"). In that event, Transporter shall schedule or curtail service using the following priorities.
(a) Priority and Scheduling of Make-up Quantities. Make-up quantities to correct Imbalances shall have the lowest priority of service on the Pipeline System. Priority within this class shall be determined on a first-come, first-served basis. For operational purposes, Transporter shall have the right to schedule make-up quantities at a higher priority, without liability to any Shipper or any other
(b) Priority and Scheduling of Interruptible Transportation Service. Interruptible transportation service shall be scheduled when, and to the extent that capacity is available in Transporter's existing facilities after first scheduling all Firm transportation service and considering all Pipeline System operating requirements. Interruptible Shippers paying the maximum rate shall have the highest priority among all Interruptible Shippers. Transporter may, but is not obligated, to provide transportation at a discounted rate, and shall give priority from the least discount to the greatest discount. If two or more Shippers are paying the same rate for Interruptible service and there is insufficient capacity to serve all Shippers paying such rate, Transporter shall provide service pro rata based on the quotient of the quantity nominated by each Shipper at the Constrained Point divided by the total quantity nominated by all such Shippers sharing the priority.
(c) Priority of Firm Transportation Service. Firm transportation service shall have the highest priority on the Pipeline System. In the event Transporter has insufficient capacity on a segment of its Pipeline System to schedule all Nominations for service, Transporter shall allocate the available capacity on the affected segment first among Firm Shippers nominating to Receipt Point(s) upstream of the capacity constraint and Delivery Point(s) downstream of the capacity constraint on a pro rata basis based on each such Shipper's MDQ.
8.2 Transporter's application of the priorities hereunder shall be subject to the actions of other Interconnecting Parties delivering or receiving gas on behalf of Shippers.
8.3 Available capacity at any Receipt Point(s), Delivery Point(s) or any other point on or through the Pipeline System will be based on Transporter's sole evaluation of Operating Conditions on its Pipeline System, including, but not limited to, pipeline pressures, compression, Interconnecting Parties' pipeline pressures, limitations and capabilities, and other Operating Conditions as they exist from time to time. Available capacity may be limited at Transporter's discretion.
9. CURTAILMENT

9.2 Any curtailment of service shall be in reverse order of priority as set forth in Section 8 of this Operating Statement. An Interruptible Shipper paying a discounted rate may alter its priority of service by agreeing to pay the maximum rate or by accepting a lesser discount acceptable to Transporter. Such rate adjustment shall amend the Gas Transportation Service Agreement and must be agreed to in writing by both Parties prior to the initiation of the curtailment or interruption.
9.3 Transporter shall not be liable for any loss or damage to any person or property caused, in whole or in part, by any Interruption or curtailment of service, except to the extent caused by Transporter's gross negligence or willful misconduct. 10. BALANCING AND PENALTIES
10.1 Imbalance Resolution. Shipper shall use its best efforts to keep all Imbalances to a minimum and shall not intentionally create or fail to avoid any Imbalances in order to take advantage of changes in the market price of gas. From time to time, differences may arise between the total quantity of gas received at the Receipt Point(s) and the Equivalent Quantity allocated to and delivered for the account of Shipper at the Delivery Point(s). Transporter shall be entitled to manage its receipts from and deliveries to Shipper so as to keep any Imbalances as near to zero as practicable.
(a) If at the end of any Month, the Imbalance created due to the difference between receipts and deliveries under the Gas Transportation Service Agreement for such Month is in excess of five percent (5%), then the entire current Month Imbalance will be cashed out effective on the last day of such Month pursuant to Sections 10.2 and 10.3, as applicable, when the Shipper is billed by Transporter for the Month in which the Imbalance occurred. Shippers exceeding the five percent (5%) imbalance threshold shall not be entitled to reduce the current Month Imbalance by trading Imbalances or nominating Imbalance Resolution Gas during the following Month.
(b) Shippers having Imbalances which are five percent (5%) or less at the end of any Month shall endeavor to bring such Imbalance to zero percent (0%) of actual deliveries within the following Month. If at the end of the following Month the prior period Imbalance is greater than five percent (5%), then Shipper shall be cashed out pursuant to this Section, as applicable, and the Imbalance shall be brought to zero percent (0%). Transporter and Shipper may enter into separate imbalance agreements to take into consideration special unique circumstances.
10.2 Cashout of Current Month Imbalance Reflecting the Over-delivery of Shipper's Gas. If at the end of any Month the quantity of gas delivered for the account of Shipper for such Month is less than the quantity of gas received for the account of Shipper for such Month, adjusted for applicable Fuel Reimbursement, and such current Month Imbalance exceeds five percent (5%) of Shipper's current Month deliveries, then the excess of such current Month Imbalance shall be cashed out by Transporter. Such cashout shall be accomplished by Transporter purchasing from Shipper the entire current Month Imbalance quantity. These purchases shall be made at a rate equal to seventy-five percent (75%) of Index Price Two and shall be applied as a credit on Shipper's following monthly statement. These purchases shall not be made by Transporter if the current Month Imbalance under the Gas Transportation Service Agreement is five (5) Dth or less.
10.3 Cashout of Current Month Imbalance Reflecting the Under-delivery of Shipper's Gas. If at the end of any Month the quantity of gas delivered for the account of Shipper for such Month is less than the quantity of gas received for the account of Shipper for such Month, adjusted for applicable Fuel Reimbursement, and such current Month Imbalance exceeds five percent (5%) of Shipper's current Month deliveries, then the excess of such current Month Imbalance shall be cashed out by Transporter. Such cashout shall be accomplished by Transporter selling to Shipper the entire current Month Imbalance quantity. These sales shall be made at a rate equal to the sum of one hundred twenty-five percent (125%) of Index Price One plus the CIG TI Transportation Rate and shall be applied as a charge on Shipper's following monthly statement. These sales shall not be made by Transporter if the current Month Imbalance under Gas Transportation Service Agreement is five (5) Dth or less.
10.4 Imbalance Upon Termination of Transportation Service. Any Imbalance remaining following the termination of the Gas Transportation Service Agreement shall be eliminated during the Month following the Month in which termination occurs, in accordance with Section 10.1. If the Gas Transportation Service Agreement is terminated and service continues under another Gas Transportation Service Agreement, the Imbalance may upon Shipper's request be transferred to new Gas Transportation Service Agreement and the provisions of this Section 10 shall apply to the combined new Imbalance as if accumulated under a single Gas Transportation Service Agreement.
10.5 Imbalance Trading. A Shipper may trade Imbalance gas among different Gas Transportation Service Agreements which it holds and those held by other Shippers to eliminate or reduce Imbalances under those Gas Transportation Service Agreements. Any trade of Imbalance gas shall not cause Transporter to receive less value than Transporter would have received had the trade not occurred. Any Imbalance trade shall be subject to the following conditions:
(a) Shippers are responsible for making whatever arrangements they deem necessary to finalize and document the Imbalance trade among themselves.
(b) Shippers may request Transporter, in writing, to post notice of Imbalances available for trade on Transporter's Electronic Bulletin Board on their behalf.
(c) Only trades which have the effect of reducing a Shipper's Imbalance under a Gas Transportation Service Agreement shall be permitted. Shipper must notify Transporter in writing of the material terms of the trade arrangement. Shipper's written notice will be deemed to be Shipper's direction to Transporter to make the Imbalance trade on Shipper's account.
(d) Written notice from each of the involved Shippers must be received by Transporter no later than the fifth (5th) Business Day following the Month the Imbalance was to be resolved, unless otherwise agreed to by Transporter.
(e) The trading of Imbalances will be subject to Transporter's approval based upon operational considerations. Transporter will approve or disapprove trade requests within three (3) Business Days.
Transporter shall not be responsible for any liabilities incurred by a Shipper as a result of Transporter performing a trade arrangement in accordance with the written notice of the involved Shippers. Any change of fact, including but not limited to retroactive adjustments, which affect the beginning Imbalance, shall not rescind or otherwise modify any trade arrangement Shippers have requested the Transporter to perform.
10.6 Operational Imbalances. At no time shall Transporter be required to receive quantities at the Receipt Point(s) for Shipper's account in excess of the quantities Shipper will accept at the Delivery Point(s) on a concurrent basis. At no time shall Transporter be required to deliver quantities at the Delivery Point(s) for Shipper's account in excess of the quantities Shipper causes to be received by Transporter at the Receipt Point(s) on a concurrent basis, less applicable adjustments for Fuel Reimbursement. If Shipper fails to modify Nominations as directed by Transporter to reduce an operational Imbalance, Transporter may, among other remedies, suspend or terminate service.
10.7 Imbalance Report. Transporter shall determine and make available to the Shipper, in the scheduling business system on Transporter's EBB, the cumulative daily Imbalance quantity applicable to each Service Agreement through the last day of the Month to identify the end-of-Month Imbalance quantity on each Service Agreement. Any disputes regarding the accuracy of the end-of-Month Imbalance quantity shall not be sufficient reason for delaying correction of the Imbalance or withholding payment of the monthly cashout charges.
11. FUEL REIMBURSEMENT
Shipper shall include, and Transporter shall have the right to retain, as Fuel Reimbursement, a percentage of the gas delivered by Shipper at the Receipt Point(s) under a Gas Transportation Service Agreement. Unless otherwise specified in the Gas Transportation Service Agreement, the Fuel Reimbursement Percentage shall be the maximum Fuel Reimbursement Percentage as set forth from time to time in the Statement of Rates in this Operating Statement. The Fuel Reimbursement Percentage shall be subject to change effective each January 1, to be equal to the Fuel Reimbursement Percentage approved by the Colorado PUC for gas transportation service provided by Transporter pursuant to its effective Colorado PUC gas tariff. The Fuel Reimbursement Percentage shall be computed as the percentage of Transporter's total system fuel, lost and unaccounted-for gas quantities, as adjusted for Transporter-owned storage, plant fuel and gas shrinkage, to Transporter's total Pipeline System throughput for the twelve-month period ending June 30 of the previous Year.

Such Monthly statement and invoice shall set forth (i) the charges due for the preceding Month; (ii) the total quantity of gas, stated in Dekatherms, received from and delivered to Shipper hereunder during the preceding Month(s), and the amount due therefore; and if applicable, (iii) information sufficient to explain and support any adjustments made by Transporter in determining the amount billed, including any cashout credits for purchases of oversupply of Shipper's Gas or cashout charges for gas supplies sold by Transporter to the Shipper pursuant to Section 10. If the bill is found to be incorrect by Transporter, and in the event of an overpayment, Transporter will refund the amount of overpayment or credit the amount of overpayment to the next bill rendered.
12.4 Both Transporter and Shipper shall have the right at their own expense to examine and audit at any reasonable time the books, records (including measurement, billing and payment) and charts of the other to the extent necessary to verify the accuracy of any statements or charges made under or pursuant to any of the provisions of Shipper's Gas Transportation Service Agreement. Upon request, Shipper shall also make available to Transporter for audit purposes any relevant records of Interconnecting Parties to which Shipper conveniently has access. A formal audit of accounts shall not be made more often than once each Year.
